(c) Confusion Matrix

contrasts(Weekly$Direction)
##      Up
## Down  0
## Up    1
test.pred.prob  <- predict(glm.fit, newdata = Weekly,type="response")
test.pred <- rep("Down", length(test.pred.prob))
test.pred[test.pred.prob>0.5] <- "Up"

# confusion matrix
confusionMatrix(data = as.factor(test.pred),
                reference = Weekly$Direction)

The model has low sensitivity(0.11157) and high specificity(0.92066), which means for true Down direction, only 11% is predicted correctly, and for true Up direction, 92% is predicted correctly. Positive predictive value and negative predictive value are 0.53 and 0.56 respectively, which means in the predicted Up direction, 53% is correct, and in the predicted Down direction, 56% is correct.

(e) Logistic Regression using partial data

rowTrain <- which(Weekly$Year != 2009 & Weekly$Year != 2010)

glm.fit2 <- glm(Direction~Lag1+Lag2, 
               data = Weekly, subset = rowTrain, family = binomial)
summary(glm.fit2)

(f) LDA & QDA

# LDA
library(MASS)
## 
## Attaching package: 'MASS'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
lda.fit <- lda(Direction ~ Lag1 + Lag2, 
               data = Weekly, subset = rowTrain)
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = Weekly[-rowTrain,])

mean(lda.pred$class !=  Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain]) # test error
## [1] 0.4230769
roc.lda <- roc(Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain], lda.pred$posterior[,2], 
               levels = c("Down", "Up"))
plot(roc.lda, legacy.axes = TRUE, print.auc = TRUE)

# QDA
qda.fit <- qda(Direction ~ Lag1 + Lag2, 
               data = Weekly, subset = rowTrain)
qda.pred <- predict(qda.fit, newdata = Weekly[-rowTrain,])

mean(qda.pred$class !=  Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain]) # test error
## [1] 0.4423077
roc.qda <- roc(Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain], qda.pred$posterior[,2], 
               levels = c("Down", "Up"))
plot(roc.qda, legacy.axes = TRUE, print.auc = TRUE)

(g) KNN

library(class)

train.x <- Weekly[rowTrain, c(2,3)]
test.x <- Weekly[-rowTrain, c(2,3)]

# k = 1
pred.knn1 <- knn(train.x, test.x, Weekly$Direction[rowTrain], k = 1, prob = T)
mean(pred.knn1 !=  Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain]) # test error
## [1] 0.5192308
roc.knn1 <- roc(Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain], attr(pred.knn1, "prob"), levels = c("Down", "Up"))
# table(pred.knn1, test$Direction)

# k = 3
pred.knn3 <- knn(train.x, test.x, Weekly$Direction[rowTrain], k = 3, prob = T)
mean(pred.knn3 !=  Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain]) # test error
## [1] 0.4807692
roc.knn3 <- roc(Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain], attr(pred.knn3, "prob"), levels = c("Down", "Up"))

# k = 10
pred.knn10 <- knn(train.x, test.x, Weekly$Direction[rowTrain], k = 10, prob = T)
mean(pred.knn10 !=  Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain]) # test error
## [1] 0.5
roc.knn10 <- roc(Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain], attr(pred.knn10, "prob"), levels = c("Down", "Up"))

# k = 50
pred.knn50 <- knn(train.x, test.x, Weekly$Direction[rowTrain], k = 50, prob = T)
mean(pred.knn50 !=  Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain]) # test error
## [1] 0.4615385
roc.knn50 <- roc(Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain], attr(pred.knn50, "prob"), levels = c("Down", "Up"))

# k = 100
pred.knn100 <- knn(train.x, test.x, Weekly$Direction[rowTrain], k = 100, prob = T)
mean(pred.knn100 !=  Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain]) # test error
## [1] 0.4519231
roc.knn100 <- roc(Weekly$Direction[-rowTrain], attr(pred.knn100, "prob"), levels = c("Down", "Up"))

# ROC curve
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(roc.knn1, legacy.axes = T, print.auc = T, main = "K=1") 
plot(roc.knn3, legacy.axes = T, print.auc = T, main = "K=3") 
plot(roc.knn10, legacy.axes = T, print.auc = T, main = "K=10") 
plot(roc.knn50, legacy.axes = T, print.auc = T, main = "K=50")

plot(roc.knn100, legacy.axes = T, print.auc = T, main = "K=100")

From AUC calculated at K = 1, 3, 10, 50, 100, and test error results, I found that K = 50 provides the best classification. However, the prediction performance cannot be considered good. Parametric approach LDA and QDA also had poor performances in predicting the direction. Other methods such as cross-validation might be needed.
